commit d8b26ef26eaba7cc9fa85153cc7ef32bdcc643c0
Author: shaleh <shaleh>
Date:	Mon Jun 3 18:54:46 2002 +0000

    was a little over zealous in killing the last focus bug.

 src/Window.cc | 6 +-----
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 5 deletions(-)

commit 1e7ff4841aa6f839ccb090fca6f28532aaa77c51
Author: shaleh <shaleh>
Date:	Sun Jun 2 23:51:46 2002 +0000

    Fixed the crash on workspace change bug.

    The cause of the problem was blackbox attributes from a previous mapping
    affecting the current mapping of a window.	This is the right approach
    during
    startup because we want windows to return to their former state.
    However this
    is not the behaviour we want if a window is mapped and unmapped.

    What was happening was this:

    A window was mapped on workspace A and the unmapped.  It was then
    opened again
    on workspace B.  During the managing of the window the blackbox attributes
    from the last mapping were applied.  So the window believed it was on
    A while
    it was actually on B.  If the user then switches to other workspaces the
    window acts as if it were stuck because no workspace owns it.  On top
    of this
    the window is marked as being the last focus window for workspace B.  Once
    blackbox is on workspace A again the window is believed to be home.  If the
    window is then unmapped the last focus pointer on workspace B is now
    invalid
    but there is no way for blackbox to know this.  So the next time the
    current
    workspace is changed to B a crash occurs as the invalid window pointer is
    dereferenced.

    The fix in this patch is to only restore window attributes during blackbox
    startup.  As further protection against this bug I left an assert() in
    BScreen::changeWorkspaceID().

 src/Screen.cc	  | 12 +++++-------
 src/Window.cc	  | 10 +++++-----
 src/Workspace.cc |  1 -
 src/blackbox.cc  |  9 ++++-----
 4 files changed, 14 insertions(+), 18 deletions(-)

